column509:
The fort was originally constructed in 1612 to guard against the Dutch. It was a reference point for the vessels coming from Europe at that time. This old Portuguese fort stands on the beach south of Candolim, at the shore of the Mandovi River. It was initially tasked with defense of shipping and the nearby Bardez sub-district.

A freshwater spring within the fort provided water supply to the ships that used to stop by. This is how the fort got its name: Aguada, meaning watery in the Portuguese language. Crews of passing ships would often visit to replenish their freshwater stores. The Aguada Fort Lighthouse erected in 1864 is the oldest of its kind in Asia. Built in 1612, it was once the grandstand of 79 cannons. It has the capacity of storing 2,376,000 gallons of water, one of the biggest freshwater storage of the time in whole of Asia. This fort is divided in two segments: the upper part acted as fort and watering station, while the lower part served as a safe berth for Portuguese ships. Whereas the upper part has a moat, underground water storage chamber, gunpowder room, lighthouse, and bastions, it also has a secret escape passage to use during time of war and emergency. The lighthouse at the initial stage is used to emit light once in 7 minutes.

Fort Aguada was the most prized and crucial fort of Portuguese. The fort is so large that it envelops the entire peninsula at the southwestern tip of Bardez. Built on the mouth of Mandovi River, it was strategically located and was the chief defense of Portuguese against the Dutch.[1]

During the Salazar Administration, Fort Aguada was repurposed for use as a prison primarily, some claim, for Salazar's political opponents.[citation needed]

column669:
Goa is famous for tourism and various temples of various Hindu Deities.  Speciality of Goa Temples is total cleanliness and pure holiness.  You will also not find any beggar outside any temple like other places in Maharashtra.

Verna is a major Industrial Area in Goa.  Shri Devi Mahalsa Temple is an old temple there.  I understood that It's the place of origin of Devi Mahalsa.  Couldn't check whether it is true or false but the temple is well renovated and maintained.  Area of this temple is also huge like other temples at Goa.  During the Portuguese era idol of Devi Mahalsa was shifted to Mhaddol Area where today we can take darshan of Devi Mahalsa. In fact today, Mhaddol Temple is like the main temple of Devi Mahalsa.   This Verna temple is also duly renovated but it still has preserved it's own old charm and surrounding.

There are other small temples in the vicinity of this temple.  Entry is restricted to those who wear shorts, bermudas, mini skirts and or other similar outfits.   This rule is almost everywhere in all the temples at Goa.   You must visit this temple if you are at Goa and if you love visiting temples.

This remarkable location on the west coast of India is famously called the Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj Fort or Farmagudi fort, complete with a mystical park surrounding it. The fort itself is a masterpiece made of mud and stone, with a fascinating background story.

Originally built by the Muslim forces of Adil Shah with structured architecture, the fort offers breathtaking views from the top, with several sections that will captivate you, especially during the magical sunset.

People visit this place for various reasons, but most often to admire the natural beauty and create memorable experiences. The Ponda fort, located in the outskirts of Ponda city in Goa, is an ideal spot for photo sessions that can be shared on social media.

column509: This was the happiest day of my life. I had never been to a waterpark before so me and my family planned a trip to this waterpark. It was before the COVID era. There are separate changing rooms for ladies and gents including the washrooms. There are many games that we can play here and it's family friendly and kids friendly too. We can also bring our own water toys and floaters to play in the pool. There are lifeguards all over the park to keep us safe. If you want to enjoy a full waterpark better go in the morning because as the day goes by the public will increase and you will not get floaters and other accessories to play. There will be an announcement for rain dance so whenever we listen to the announcement we used to run to the dance floor to enjoy the rain. There are other activities too but i forgot the names of the activities. After exploring the water park, we went to eat food because we were super duper hungry. There are many restaurants on the first floor inside the water park and we can enjoy the food by watching others playing in the water. My niece loved the Nescafe tea sold in one of the restaurants. I wish to come here again with my family. But after reaching home our whole body was itching because of chlorinated water and we got severe tanning and it went away after a month. So please apply sunscreen before going to this waterpark.

column509:
A museum dedicated for the technological advancements till date and featuring multiple equipment/machines/tools on the theme. The museum is for the people who has interest in History, antiques etc. The museum located in Betalbatim area. A dedicated parking slot suitable for 5-6four wheel vehicle available. There is a restaurant attached to museum located at Ground floor of museum.  This restaurant is a pure veg restaurant offering breakfast as well as Lunch menu. A small bar counter is also available with restaurant.
Coming back to museum,the entrance is at ground floor and the ticket of rs 200 per adult and 100 per child . The preferred transaction for tickets is cash payment. Once the ticket charges paid, the guide takes to show the museum displayed at first and second floor of the building.

Variety of utensils,decoratives are displayed at museum..
What I liked the most is the museum shows the journey and progress of technology by means of most old audio player and latest type of audio player.
Similarly measurement equipment, storage utensils, telephones, clocks, calculator, typewriter etc are displayed.
After view of museum the guide takes us down in the front lawn of museum. They show the variety of bonsai developed by them in last 30 years.

Overall it's a great experience. Recommended one visit by people who love antiques and Historical equipments.

column669:
Church of Saint Francis of Assisi, Roman Catholic church situated in the main square of Old Goa, 6 miles (10 kilometres) east of Panaji, Goa’s state capital. The Church of St. Francis of Assisi, together with a convent, was established by eight Portuguese Franciscan friars who landed in Goa in 1517.

The original church began as a small chapel, which was modified to a church in 1521 and consecrated in 1602. That building was replaced by the current structure, erected in 1661. The present-day church is a mixture of styles. Its exterior decoration is in the simple Tuscan order, but its interior—especially the main altar—is richly Baroque with Corinthian features. The three-tier exterior facade has two distinct octagonal towers, one on each side, and a small niche that houses a statue of Mary. The church’s interior includes a richly ornamental niche with a tabernacle supported by the Four Evangelists on the main altar. Above the tabernacle are two large statues, one of St. Francis of Assisi and the other of the crucified Christ. The church’s gilded interior is decorated with paintings of events in the life of St. Francis, carved woodwork, additional statues, and frescos with intricate floral designs.

column669:
The Quepem Dam is a historical and scenic destination in Goa. It is not a highly popular tourist attraction, but still worth a visit if you are staying in Quepem or in the area.

However, it is advised to avoid visiting the dam in the evenings or at night as there is low visibility, which can make the place somewhat frightening. The dam is a great place to relax and enjoy the serene surroundings, including the tranquil sound of water and the peaceful environment. Fishing is also a popular activity at the dam.

For those who love to cycle, the dam offers a refreshing cycling experience, particularly in the evenings. While the dam is well-built, it is important to be careful of broken bottles scattered around the area.

The Quepem Dam is one of the oldest dams in Goa, with a small weir on the side, making it a suitable place for a summer picnic or a swim. During the monsoon season, the dam becomes even more stunning, but it is not recommended to go for a bath during the rainy season.

Overall, while the Quepem Dam may not be the most thrilling tourist destination, it is a nice place to spend a peaceful and relaxing time in Goa

The evening in and around this church became crowded and colourful. The roads were crammed of people , all in a festive mood. Footpath shops sprang up. The church was illuminated wonderfully well. We went up the stairs and watched the road from every level. View of the church from the road and view of the road from the church both were wonderful. I had a very enjoyable morning just watching the fair all around. Families had come out in droves to buy roadside knick knacks and to take part in the festivities. Decided to come back and see the church in daylight again.It can be enjoyed by anyone from any religion.

column669:
Must visit water falls once in life time.
Best experience for trekking through rivers during monsoon season.
Beautiful place to swim and bath.
If you are not interested in trekking for 11 kms you can travel to water falls by government jeeps only from kulem. You have to park your private vehicles in kulem and go through only government jeeps for ₹500 per person(maximum 7 members in a jeep). and they also charge extra ₹100 per person while starting your journey to falls.
After reaching to dudhsagar water falls after 1hr journey in jeep. You have to walk 1-2 kms definitely.
They way is full of rocks and boulders ,you have to walk very carefully and slowly. There is no flat land at all it is full of rocks, one step wrong you may affect with leg fracture or dislocation of bone orany other leg issues.
After reaching to water you can swim upto 1hr because the jeeps only wait for 1hr30mins from dropping time after that they charge extra money.
Change your dresses before reaching water falls because there is no proper dress changing rooms here only 2 or 3 available. And some restrooms.
Best experience with friends here ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️

We had horrific experience in so-called parking while visiting this waterfall.
There is a kind of scam run by locals there. They don't allow to park anywhere (and there is a lot of empty space all around) except to one designated area which they intentionally made accident prone. To leave "parking lot", you have to cross very narrow bridge (ok for smaller cars and scooters). Something as big as a 4 wheel will put you in big trouble and money extortion situation.
When we decided to get some tea from small vendor (who was apparently the leader of the extortion gang) his comrads/villagers made some issue and blamed us. Since this place is in deep jungle, there is absolutely no way to communicate with outer world - no mobile signal for any operator , no police station , no authorities AT ALL. We were left in mercy of local tribe and situation was getting worse with every minute. Our car  and ourselves (6 adults, including a foreigner) were blocked and threatened! They demanded 12000 rs for some kind of scratch to another car which was few metres away ... After very hot arguments we had to give up.
The thing is that you are there on your own , absolutely helpless in case the people decide they need some extra money ...
It's better to go to some government run or organised places like Netrawali for example. Or be prepared by all means for unexpected

column509:
If you are an adventure lover and nature seeker, this should certainly go in the list of places to visit. To experience this spectacle, you need to take a trek route which is about 10 kms (onward and return put together).

When you park your vehicles, you can visit Mahadev temple which was built centuries ago. Though it's a small temple, it is very well maintained and gives a very pleasant and divine feeling. You have a water stream passing right next to the temple where you can relax and enjoy the nature.

Before you begin your trek, if you want to fill your tummy with some local made snacks, you have couple of stalls right next to the entrance.

During the trek, you come across many beautiful water streams all through the journey as you pass through the dense Western ghats. Need to be cautious as you pass through these streams as there's a high possibility that you come across leaches and snakes during the course of your journey.

The first glimpse of the fall itself is so magnificent. If you would like to get a bit closer to the waterfall and get drenched yourself just by sitting right next to the mainstream, you need to have a bit of energy and power as you need to climb some steep rocks to make it.

It is worth taking this as the feeling is so surreal. My personal suggestion of you are adventure lover is it is a must visit.

The tower, which dates back to the 16th century, offers breathtaking views of the surrounding landscape, including the sea and nearby churches. The climb to the top is a bit of a workout, but the views from the top are well worth it. The tower is also a great spot for photography, both during the day and at sunset. The staff were also very helpful and friendly. Overall, St. Augustine Tower is a great place to visit if you're looking to take in some of Goa's rich history and beautiful scenery.

column509:
Aguada Fort, a 1612 Portuguese fortress located in Goa, is a historic landmark that offers visitors a glimpse into the state's rich cultural past. The fort, which is situated on a hilltop overlooking the Arabian Sea, provides sweeping ocean views and a fascinating look at Goa's colonial history.

One of the things that immediately stands out about Aguada Fort is its size. The fort is quite large and features a variety of structures, including a lighthouse that was erected in 1864. Although the fort is in a state of disrepair, it is still an impressive structure that is worth exploring.

However, despite its size and historical significance, there is not much to see at Aguada Fort. Most of the structures are in ruins, and there are few exhibits or artifacts to explain the history of the fort. The abandoned lighthouse is also off-limits to visitors, which is disappointing.

Visitors must pay an entry fee of 25 rupees for Indians and 100 rupees for foreigners to access the fort. While the fee is not particularly high, some visitors may feel that it is not worth the cost given the lack of things to see.

One of the highlights of Aguada Fort is the stunning view of the Arabian Sea from the hilltop. You can see the water from the fort, and the view is particularly breathtaking at sunset. This makes the fort a popular spot for photographers and tourists looking to take in the natural beauty of the region.

Overall, Aguada Fort is an interesting historical site that provides a glimpse into Goa's colonial past. While the lack of exhibits and the state of disrepair may be disappointing for some visitors, the stunning views of the ocean and the natural beauty of the region make it worth a visit for those interested in history and architecture.

Aguada Fort and Jail are historic landmarks located in Goa, India. Aguada Fort, built in the 17th century, is a beautiful piece of architecture that boasts stunning views of the Arabian Sea. It is a perfect place to visit for anyone interested in history or architecture.

The fort is well-maintained and provides an impressive backdrop for photo opportunities. The lighthouse and the ramparts offer breathtaking views of the sea, which makes it an ideal place for a sunset walk or a picnic. The fort also has a small museum that showcases the history of the area, which is informative and interesting.

The nearby Aguada Jail is another fascinating historical site. The jail is now a museum, and it offers a glimpse into the harsh realities of colonial times. The prison cells are a sobering reminder of the inhumane treatment of prisoners in the past, and the exhibits provide a comprehensive overview of the prison's history.

Overall, Aguada Fort and Jail are two must-visit historical sites in Goa. The fort's beautiful architecture and stunning views are a treat for visitors, and the museum inside the jail offers a glimpse into the area's dark past. I highly recommend visiting these sites for anyone interested in history, architecture, or simply looking for a unique and memorable experience in Goa.
